1. Container Management
  
These commands handle the lifecycle of your active or stopped containers.

docker run [image]: Creates and starts a container from an image. (e.g., docker run -d -p 80:80 nginx)

docker ps: Lists all currently running containers. Add -a (docker ps -a) to see stopped containers as well.

docker start [container]: Starts a stopped container.

docker stop [container]: Gracefully stops a running container.

docker restart [container]: Stops and then starts a container.

docker kill [container]: Forcefully stops a running container immediately.

docker rm [container]: Deletes a stopped container. Use -f to force delete a running one.

docker exec -it [container] [command]: Runs a command inside a running container (e.g., docker exec -it my_container bash to open a terminal).

docker logs [container]: Fetches the logs of a container. Add -f to follow the log output live.

docker cp [path] [container]:[path]: Copies files/folders between a container and your local filesystem.

docker top [container]: Displays the running processes inside a container.

docker stats: Shows a live stream of container resource usage statistics (CPU, memory, networking).
  

2. Image Management
  
These commands deal with the templates (images) used to create containers.

docker build -t [name]:[tag] [path]: Builds a Docker image from a Dockerfile located in the specified path. (e.g., docker build -t my-app:latest .)

docker pull [image]: Downloads an image from a registry (like Docker Hub).

docker push [image]: Uploads an image to a registry.

docker images: Lists all locally stored Docker images.

docker rmi [image]: Removes one or more local images.

docker tag [source_image] [target_image]: Creates a tag (target_image) that refers to a source_image.

docker history [image]: Shows the history of how an image was built.

docker commit [container] [image]: Creates a new image from a container's current changes.

  
3. Network Management
  
These commands manage how containers communicate with each other and the outside world.

docker network ls: Lists all Docker networks.

docker network create [network]: Creates a new network.

docker network rm [network]: Removes one or more networks.

docker network inspect [network]: Displays detailed information about one or more networks.

docker network connect [network] [container]: Connects a container to a network.

docker network disconnect [network] [container]: Disconnects a container from a network.

  
4. Volume Management
  
Volumes are the preferred mechanism for persisting data generated by and used by Docker containers.

docker volume ls: Lists all Docker volumes.

docker volume create [volume]: Creates a new volume.

docker volume rm [volume]: Removes an unused volume.

docker volume inspect [volume]: Displays detailed information about a volume.

  
5. System and General Info
  
Commands for interacting with the Docker engine itself and cleaning up your environment.

docker info: Displays system-wide information about your Docker installation.

docker version: Shows the Docker version information.

docker login: Logs in to a Docker registry.

docker logout: Logs out of a Docker registry.

docker system prune: A very useful cleanup command! It removes all stopped containers, unused networks, dangling images, and build cache. Add -a to wipe out all unused images, not just dangling ones.

docker inspect [object]: Returns low-level information on Docker objects (containers, images, networks, etc.) in JSON format.

docker search [term]: Searches Docker Hub for images.
